\title{Libfuzzer}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{Coverage-guided fuzzer built into LLVM for C/C++ projects. Use for fuzzing C/C++ code that can be compiled with Clang.}

\subtree{
\title{libFuzzer}
\p{libFuzzer is an in-process, coverage-guided fuzzer that is part of the LLVM project. It's the recommended starting point for fuzzing C/C++ projects due to its simplicity and integration with the LLVM toolchain. While libFuzzer has been in maintenance-only mode since late 2022, it is easier to install and use than its alternatives, has wide support, and will be maintained for the foreseeable future.}

\subtree{
\title{When to Use}
\pre{\startverb
| Fuzzer | Best For | Complexity |
|--------|----------|------------|
| libFuzzer | Quick setup, single-project fuzzing | Low |
| AFL++ | Multi-core fuzzing, diverse mutations | Medium |
| LibAFL | Custom fuzzers, research projects | High |
| Honggfuzz | Hardware-based coverage | Medium |
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Choose libFuzzer when:}}

\ul{
\li{You need a simple, quick setup for C/C++ code}
\li{Project uses Clang for compilation}
\li{Single-core fuzzing is sufficient initially}
\li{Transitioning to AFL++ later is an option (harnesses are compatible)}
}

\p{\strong{Note:} Fuzzing harnesses written for libFuzzer are compatible with AFL++, making it easy to transition if you need more advanced features like better multi-core support.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Quick Start}
\pre{\startverb
#include <stdint.h>
#include <stddef.h>

extern "C" int LLVMFuzzerTestOneInput(const uint8_t *data, size_t size) {
    // Validate input if needed
    if (size < 1) return 0;

    // Call your target function with fuzzer-provided data
    my_target_function(data, size);

    return 0;
}
\stopverb}

\p{Compile and run:}

\pre{\startverb
clang++ -fsanitize=fuzzer,address -g -O2 harness.cc target.cc -o fuzz
mkdir corpus/
./fuzz corpus/
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Installation}
\subtree{
\title{Prerequisites}
\ul{
\li{LLVM/Clang compiler (includes libFuzzer)}
\li{LLVM tools for coverage analysis (optional)}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Linux (Ubuntu/Debian)}
\pre{\startverb
apt install clang llvm
\stopverb}

\p{For the latest LLVM version:}

\pre{\startverb
# Add LLVM repository from apt.llvm.org
# Then install specific version, e.g.:
apt install clang-18 llvm-18
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{macOS}
\pre{\startverb
# Using Homebrew
brew install llvm

# Or using Nix
nix-env -i clang
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Windows}
\p{Install Clang through Visual Studio. Refer to [Microsoft's documentation](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/cpp/build/clang-support-msbuild?view=msvc-170) for setup instructions.}

\p{\strong{Recommendation:} If possible, fuzz on a local x86_64 VM or rent one on DigitalOcean, AWS, or Hetzner. Linux provides the best support for libFuzzer.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Verification}
\pre{\startverb
clang++ --version
# Should show LLVM version information
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Writing a Harness}
\subtree{
\title{Harness Structure}
\p{The harness is the entry point for the fuzzer. libFuzzer calls the \code{\startverb LLVMFuzzerTestOneInput\stopverb} function repeatedly with different inputs.}

\pre{\startverb
#include <stdint.h>
#include <stddef.h>

extern "C" int LLVMFuzzerTestOneInput(const uint8_t *data, size_t size) {
    // 1. Optional: Validate input size
    if (size < MIN_REQUIRED_SIZE) {
        return 0;  // Reject inputs that are too small
    }

    // 2. Optional: Convert raw bytes to structured data
    // Example: Parse two integers from byte array
    if (size >= 2 * sizeof(uint32_t)) {
        uint32_t a = *(uint32_t*)(data);
        uint32_t b = *(uint32_t*)(data + sizeof(uint32_t));
        my_function(a, b);
    }

    // 3. Call target function
    target_function(data, size);

    // 4. Always return 0 (non-zero reserved for future use)
    return 0;
}
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Harness Rules}
\pre{\startverb
| Do | Don't |
|----|-------|
| Handle all input types (empty, huge, malformed) | Call `exit()` - stops fuzzing process |
| Join all threads before returning | Leave threads running |
| Keep harness fast and simple | Add excessive logging or complexity |
| Maintain determinism | Use random number generators or read `/dev/random` |
| Reset global state between runs | Rely on state from previous executions |
| Use narrow, focused targets | Mix unrelated data formats (PNG + TCP) in one harness |
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Rationale:}}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Speed matters:} Aim for 100s-1000s executions per second per core}
\li{\strong{Reproducibility:} Crashes must be reproducible after fuzzing completes}
\li{\strong{Isolation:} Each execution should be independent}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Using FuzzedDataProvider for Complex Inputs}
\p{For complex inputs (strings, multiple parameters), use the \code{\startverb FuzzedDataProvider\stopverb} helper:}

\pre{\startverb
#include <stdint.h>
#include <stddef.h>
#include "FuzzedDataProvider.h"  // From LLVM project

extern "C" int LLVMFuzzerTestOneInput(const uint8_t *data, size_t size) {
    FuzzedDataProvider fuzzed_data(data, size);

    // Extract structured data
    size_t allocation_size = fuzzed_data.ConsumeIntegral<size_t>();
    std::vector<char> str1 = fuzzed_data.ConsumeBytesWithTerminator<char>(32, 0xFF);
    std::vector<char> str2 = fuzzed_data.ConsumeBytesWithTerminator<char>(32, 0xFF);

    // Call target with extracted data
    char* result = concat(&str1[0], str1.size(), &str2[0], str2.size(), allocation_size);
    if (result != NULL) {
        free(result);
    }

    return 0;
}
\stopverb}

\p{Download \code{\startverb FuzzedDataProvider.h\stopverb} from the [LLVM repository](https://github.com/llvm/llvm-project/blob/main/compiler-rt/include/fuzzer/FuzzedDataProvider.h).}
}

\subtree{
\title{Interleaved Fuzzing}
\p{Use a single harness to test multiple related functions:}

\pre{\startverb
extern "C" int LLVMFuzzerTestOneInput(const uint8_t *data, size_t size) {
    if (size < 1 + 2 * sizeof(int32_t)) {
        return 0;
    }

    uint8_t mode = data[0];
    int32_t numbers[2];
    memcpy(numbers, data + 1, 2 * sizeof(int32_t));

    // Select function based on first byte
    switch (mode % 4) {
        case 0: add(numbers[0], numbers[1]); break;
        case 1: subtract(numbers[0], numbers[1]); break;
        case 2: multiply(numbers[0], numbers[1]); break;
        case 3: divide(numbers[0], numbers[1]); break;
    }

    return 0;
}
\stopverb}

\blockquote{\strong{See Also:} For detailed harness writing techniques, patterns for handling complex inputs, structure-aware fuzzing, and protobuf-based fuzzing, see the \strong{fuzz-harness-writing} technique skill.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Compilation}
\subtree{
\title{Basic Compilation}
\p{The key flag is \code{\startverb -fsanitize=fuzzer\stopverb}, which:}

\ul{
\li{Links the libFuzzer runtime (provides \code{\startverb main\stopverb} function)}
\li{Enables SanitizerCoverage instrumentation for coverage tracking}
\li{Disables built-in functions like \code{\startverb memcmp\stopverb}}
}

\pre{\startverb
clang++ -fsanitize=fuzzer -g -O2 harness.cc target.cc -o fuzz
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Flags explained:}}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb -fsanitize=fuzzer\stopverb}: Enable libFuzzer}
\li{\code{\startverb -g\stopverb}: Add debug symbols (helpful for crash analysis)}
\li{\code{\startverb -O2\stopverb}: Production-level optimizations (recommended for fuzzing)}
\li{\code{\startverb -DNO_MAIN\stopverb}: Define macro if your code has a \code{\startverb main\stopverb} function}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{With Sanitizers}
\p{\strong{AddressSanitizer (recommended):}}

\pre{\startverb
clang++ -fsanitize=fuzzer,address -g -O2 -U_FORTIFY_SOURCE harness.cc target.cc -o fuzz
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Multiple sanitizers:}}

\pre{\startverb
clang++ -fsanitize=fuzzer,address,undefined -g -O2 harness.cc target.cc -o fuzz
\stopverb}

\blockquote{\strong{See Also:} For detailed sanitizer configuration, common issues, ASAN_OPTIONS flags, and advanced sanitizer usage, see the \strong{address-sanitizer} and \strong{undefined-behavior-sanitizer} technique skills.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Build Flags}
\pre{\startverb
| Flag | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| `-fsanitize=fuzzer` | Enable libFuzzer runtime and instrumentation |
| `-fsanitize=address` | Enable AddressSanitizer (memory error detection) |
| `-fsanitize=undefined` | Enable UndefinedBehaviorSanitizer |
| `-fsanitize=fuzzer-no-link` | Instrument without linking fuzzer (for libraries) |
| `-g` | Include debug symbols |
| `-O2` | Production optimization level |
| `-U_FORTIFY_SOURCE` | Disable fortification (can interfere with ASan) |
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Building Static Libraries}
\p{For projects that produce static libraries:}

\ol{
\li{Build the library with fuzzing instrumentation:}
}

\pre{\startverb
export CC=clang CFLAGS="-fsanitize=fuzzer-no-link -fsanitize=address"
export CXX=clang++ CXXFLAGS="$CFLAGS"
./configure --enable-shared=no
make
\stopverb}

\ol{
\li{Link the static library with your harness:}
}

\pre{\startverb
clang++ -fsanitize=fuzzer -fsanitize=address harness.cc libmylib.a -o fuzz
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{CMake Integration}
\pre{\startverb
project(FuzzTarget)
cmake_minimum_required(VERSION 3.0)

add_executable(fuzz main.cc harness.cc)
target_compile_definitions(fuzz PRIVATE NO_MAIN=1)
target_compile_options(fuzz PRIVATE -g -O2 -fsanitize=fuzzer -fsanitize=address)
target_link_libraries(fuzz -fsanitize=fuzzer -fsanitize=address)
\stopverb}

\p{Build with:}

\pre{\startverb
cmake -DCMAKE_C_COMPILER=clang -DCMAKE_CXX_COMPILER=clang++ .
cmake --build .
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Corpus Management}
\subtree{
\title{Creating Initial Corpus}
\p{Create a directory for the corpus (can start empty):}

\pre{\startverb
mkdir corpus/
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Optional but recommended:} Provide seed inputs (valid example files):}

\pre{\startverb
# For a PNG parser:
cp examples/*.png corpus/

# For a protocol parser:
cp test_packets/*.bin corpus/
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Benefits of seed inputs:}}

\ul{
\li{Fuzzer doesn't start from scratch}
\li{Reaches valid code paths faster}
\li{Significantly improves effectiveness}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Corpus Structure}
\p{The corpus directory contains:}

\ul{
\li{Input files that trigger unique code paths}
\li{Minimized versions (libFuzzer automatically minimizes)}
\li{Named by content hash (e.g., \code{\startverb a9993e364706816aba3e25717850c26c9cd0d89d\stopverb})}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Corpus Minimization}
\p{libFuzzer automatically minimizes corpus entries during fuzzing. To explicitly minimize:}

\pre{\startverb
mkdir minimized_corpus/
./fuzz -merge=1 minimized_corpus/ corpus/
\stopverb}

\p{This creates a deduplicated, minimized corpus in \code{\startverb minimized_corpus/\stopverb}.}

\blockquote{\strong{See Also:} For corpus creation strategies, seed selection, format-specific corpus building, and corpus maintenance, see the \strong{fuzzing-corpus} technique skill.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Running Campaigns}
\subtree{
\title{Basic Run}
\pre{\startverb
./fuzz corpus/
\stopverb}

\p{This runs until a crash is found or you stop it (Ctrl+C).}
}

\subtree{
\title{Recommended: Continue After Crashes}
\pre{\startverb
./fuzz -fork=1 -ignore_crashes=1 corpus/
\stopverb}

\p{The \code{\startverb -fork\stopverb} and \code{\startverb -ignore_crashes\stopverb} flags (experimental but widely used) allow fuzzing to continue after finding crashes.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Common Options}
\p{\strong{Control input size:}}

\pre{\startverb
./fuzz -max_len=4000 corpus/
\stopverb}

\p{Rule of thumb: 2x the size of minimal realistic input.}

\p{\strong{Set timeout:}}

\pre{\startverb
./fuzz -timeout=2 corpus/
\stopverb}

\p{Abort test cases that run longer than 2 seconds.}

\p{\strong{Use a dictionary:}}

\pre{\startverb
./fuzz -dict=./format.dict corpus/
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Close stdout/stderr (speed up fuzzing):}}

\pre{\startverb
./fuzz -close_fd_mask=3 corpus/
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{See all options:}}

\pre{\startverb
./fuzz -help=1
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Multi-Core Fuzzing}
\p{\strong{Option 1: Jobs and workers (recommended):}}

\pre{\startverb
./fuzz -jobs=4 -workers=4 -fork=1 -ignore_crashes=1 corpus/
\stopverb}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb -jobs=4\stopverb}: Run 4 sequential campaigns}
\li{\code{\startverb -workers=4\stopverb}: Process jobs in parallel with 4 processes}
\li{Test cases are shared between jobs}
}

\p{\strong{Option 2: Fork mode:}}

\pre{\startverb
./fuzz -fork=4 -ignore_crashes=1 corpus/
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Note:} For serious multi-core fuzzing, consider switching to AFL++, Honggfuzz, or LibAFL.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Re-executing Test Cases}
\p{\strong{Re-run a single crash:}}

\pre{\startverb
./fuzz ./crash-a9993e364706816aba3e25717850c26c9cd0d89d
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Test all inputs in a directory without fuzzing:}}

\pre{\startverb
./fuzz -runs=0 corpus/
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Interpreting Output}
\p{When fuzzing runs, you'll see statistics like:}

\pre{\startverb
INFO: Seed: 3517090860
INFO: Loaded 1 modules (9 inline 8-bit counters)
#2      INITED cov: 3 ft: 4 corp: 1/1b exec/s: 0 rss: 26Mb
#57     NEW    cov: 4 ft: 5 corp: 2/4b lim: 4 exec/s: 0 rss: 26Mb
\stopverb}

\pre{\startverb
| Output | Meaning |
|--------|---------|
| `INITED` | Fuzzing initialized |
| `NEW` | New coverage found, added to corpus |
| `REDUCE` | Input minimized while keeping coverage |
| `cov: N` | Number of coverage edges hit |
| `corp: X/Yb` | Corpus size: X entries, Y total bytes |
| `exec/s: N` | Executions per second |
| `rss: NMb` | Resident memory usage |
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{On crash:}}

\pre{\startverb
==11672== ERROR: libFuzzer: deadly signal
artifact_prefix='./'; Test unit written to ./crash-a9993e364706816aba3e25717850c26c9cd0d89d
0x61,0x62,0x63,
abc
Base64: YWJj
\stopverb}

\p{The crash is saved to \code{\startverb ./crash-<hash>\stopverb} with the input shown in hex, UTF-8, and Base64.}

\p{\strong{Reproducibility:} Use \code{\startverb -seed=<value>\stopverb} to reproduce a fuzzing campaign (single-core only).}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Fuzzing Dictionary}
\p{Dictionaries help the fuzzer discover interesting inputs faster by providing hints about the input format.}

\subtree{
\title{Dictionary Format}
\p{Create a text file with quoted strings (one per line):}

\pre{\startverb
# Lines starting with '#' are comments

# Magic bytes
magic="\x89PNG"
magic2="IEND"

# Keywords
"GET"
"POST"
"Content-Type"

# Hex sequences
delimiter="\xFF\xD8\xFF"
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Using a Dictionary}
\pre{\startverb
./fuzz -dict=./format.dict corpus/
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Generating a Dictionary}
\p{\strong{From header files:}}

\pre{\startverb
grep -o '".*"' header.h > header.dict
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{From man pages:}}

\pre{\startverb
man curl | grep -oP '^\s*(--|-)\K\S+' | sed 's/[,.]$//' | sed 's/^/"&/; s/$/&"/' | sort -u > man.dict
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{From binary strings:}}

\pre{\startverb
strings ./binary | sed 's/^/"&/; s/$/&"/' > strings.dict
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Using LLMs:} Ask ChatGPT or similar to generate a dictionary for your format (e.g., "Generate a libFuzzer dictionary for a JSON parser").}

\blockquote{\strong{See Also:} For advanced dictionary generation, format-specific dictionaries, and dictionary optimization strategies, see the \strong{fuzzing-dictionaries} technique skill.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Coverage Analysis}
\p{While libFuzzer shows basic coverage stats (\code{\startverb cov: N\stopverb}), detailed coverage analysis requires additional tools.}

\subtree{
\title{Source-Based Coverage}
\p{\strong{1. Recompile with coverage instrumentation:}}

\pre{\startverb
clang++ -fsanitize=fuzzer -fprofile-instr-generate -fcoverage-mapping harness.cc target.cc -o fuzz
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{2. Run fuzzer to collect coverage:}}

\pre{\startverb
LLVM_PROFILE_FILE="coverage-%p.profraw" ./fuzz -runs=10000 corpus/
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{3. Merge coverage data:}}

\pre{\startverb
llvm-profdata merge -sparse coverage-*.profraw -o coverage.profdata
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{4. Generate coverage report:}}

\pre{\startverb
llvm-cov show ./fuzz -instr-profile=coverage.profdata
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{5. Generate HTML report:}}

\pre{\startverb
llvm-cov show ./fuzz -instr-profile=coverage.profdata -format=html > coverage.html
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Improving Coverage}
\p{\strong{Tips:}}

\ul{
\li{Provide better seed inputs in corpus}
\li{Use dictionaries for format-aware fuzzing}
\li{Check if harness properly exercises target}
\li{Consider structure-aware fuzzing for complex formats}
\li{Run longer campaigns (days/weeks)}
}

\blockquote{\strong{See Also:} For detailed coverage analysis techniques, identifying coverage gaps, systematic coverage improvement, and comparing coverage across fuzzers, see the \strong{coverage-analysis} technique skill.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Sanitizer Integration}
\subtree{
\title{AddressSanitizer (ASan)}
\p{ASan detects memory errors like buffer overflows and use-after-free bugs. \strong{Highly recommended for fuzzing.}}

\p{\strong{Enable ASan:}}

\pre{\startverb
clang++ -fsanitize=fuzzer,address -g -O2 -U_FORTIFY_SOURCE harness.cc target.cc -o fuzz
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Example ASan output:}}

\pre{\startverb
==1276163==ERROR: AddressSanitizer: heap-buffer-overflow on address 0x6020000c4ab1
WRITE of size 1 at 0x6020000c4ab1 thread T0
    #0 0x55555568631a in check_buf(char*, unsigned long) main.cc:13:25
    #1 0x5555556860bf in LLVMFuzzerTestOneInput harness.cc:7:3
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Configure ASan with environment variables:}}

\pre{\startverb
ASAN_OPTIONS=verbosity=1:abort_on_error=1 ./fuzz corpus/
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Important flags:}}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb verbosity=1\stopverb}: Show ASan is active}
\li{\code{\startverb detect_leaks=0\stopverb}: Disable leak detection (leaks reported at end)}
\li{\code{\startverb abort_on_error=1\stopverb}: Call \code{\startverb abort()\stopverb} instead of \code{\startverb _exit()\stopverb} on errors}
}

\p{\strong{Drawbacks:}}

\ul{
\li{2-4x slowdown}
\li{Requires ~20TB virtual memory (disable memory limits: \code{\startverb -rss_limit_mb=0\stopverb})}
\li{Best supported on Linux}
}

\blockquote{\strong{See Also:} For comprehensive ASan configuration, common pitfalls, symbolization, and combining with other sanitizers, see the \strong{address-sanitizer} technique skill.}
}

\subtree{
\title{UndefinedBehaviorSanitizer (UBSan)}
\p{UBSan detects undefined behavior like integer overflow, null pointer dereference, etc.}

\p{\strong{Enable UBSan:}}

\pre{\startverb
clang++ -fsanitize=fuzzer,undefined -g -O2 harness.cc target.cc -o fuzz
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Combine with ASan:}}

\pre{\startverb
clang++ -fsanitize=fuzzer,address,undefined -g -O2 harness.cc target.cc -o fuzz
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{MemorySanitizer (MSan)}
\p{MSan detects uninitialized memory reads. More complex to use (requires rebuilding all dependencies).}

\pre{\startverb
clang++ -fsanitize=fuzzer,memory -g -O2 harness.cc target.cc -o fuzz
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Common Sanitizer Issues}
\pre{\startverb
| Issue | Solution |
|-------|----------|
| ASan slows fuzzing too much | Use `-fsanitize-recover=address` for non-fatal errors |
| Out of memory | Set `ASAN_OPTIONS=rss_limit_mb=0` or `-rss_limit_mb=0` |
| Stack exhaustion | Increase stack size: `ASAN_OPTIONS=stack_size=8388608` |
| False positives with `_FORTIFY_SOURCE` | Use `-U_FORTIFY_SOURCE` flag |
| MSan reports in dependencies | Rebuild all dependencies with `-fsanitize=memory` |
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Real-World Examples}
\subtree{
\title{Example 1: Fuzzing libpng}
\p{libpng is a widely-used library for reading/writing PNG images. Bugs can lead to security issues.}

\p{\strong{1. Get source code:}}

\pre{\startverb
curl -L -O https://downloads.sourceforge.net/project/libpng/libpng16/1.6.37/libpng-1.6.37.tar.xz
tar xf libpng-1.6.37.tar.xz
cd libpng-1.6.37/
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{2. Install dependencies:}}

\pre{\startverb
apt install zlib1g-dev
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{3. Compile with fuzzing instrumentation:}}

\pre{\startverb
export CC=clang CFLAGS="-fsanitize=fuzzer-no-link -fsanitize=address"
export CXX=clang++ CXXFLAGS="$CFLAGS"
./configure --enable-shared=no
make
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{4. Get a harness (or write your own):}}

\pre{\startverb
curl -O https://raw.githubusercontent.com/glennrp/libpng/f8e5fa92b0e37ab597616f554bee254157998227/contrib/oss-fuzz/libpng_read_fuzzer.cc
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{5. Prepare corpus and dictionary:}}

\pre{\startverb
mkdir corpus/
curl -o corpus/input.png https://raw.githubusercontent.com/glennrp/libpng/acfd50ae0ba3198ad734e5d4dec2b05341e50924/contrib/pngsuite/iftp1n3p08.png
curl -O https://raw.githubusercontent.com/glennrp/libpng/2fff013a6935967960a5ae626fc21432807933dd/contrib/oss-fuzz/png.dict
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{6. Link and compile fuzzer:}}

\pre{\startverb
clang++ -fsanitize=fuzzer -fsanitize=address libpng_read_fuzzer.cc .libs/libpng16.a -lz -o fuzz
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{7. Run fuzzing campaign:}}

\pre{\startverb
./fuzz -close_fd_mask=3 -dict=./png.dict corpus/
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Example 2: Simple Division Bug}
\p{Harness that finds a division-by-zero bug:}

\pre{\startverb
#include <stdint.h>
#include <stddef.h>

double divide(uint32_t numerator, uint32_t denominator) {
    // Bug: No check if denominator is zero
    return numerator / denominator;
}

extern "C" int LLVMFuzzerTestOneInput(const uint8_t *data, size_t size) {
    if(size != 2 * sizeof(uint32_t)) {
        return 0;
    }

    uint32_t numerator = *(uint32_t*)(data);
    uint32_t denominator = *(uint32_t*)(data + sizeof(uint32_t));

    divide(numerator, denominator);

    return 0;
}
\stopverb}

\p{Compile and fuzz:}

\pre{\startverb
clang++ -fsanitize=fuzzer harness.cc -o fuzz
./fuzz
\stopverb}

\p{The fuzzer will quickly find inputs causing a crash.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Advanced Usage}
\subtree{
\title{Tips and Tricks}
\pre{\startverb
| Tip | Why It Helps |
|-----|--------------|
| Start with single-core, switch to AFL++ for multi-core | libFuzzer harnesses work with AFL++ |
| Use dictionaries for structured formats | 10-100x faster bug discovery |
| Close file descriptors with `-close_fd_mask=3` | Speed boost if SUT writes output |
| Set reasonable `-max_len` | Prevents wasted time on huge inputs |
| Run for days/weeks, not minutes | Coverage plateaus take time to break |
| Use seed corpus from test suites | Starts fuzzing from valid inputs |
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Structure-Aware Fuzzing}
\p{For highly structured inputs (e.g., complex protocols, file formats), use libprotobuf-mutator:}

\ul{
\li{Define input structure using Protocol Buffers}
\li{libFuzzer mutates protobuf messages (structure-preserving mutations)}
\li{Harness converts protobuf to native format}
}

\p{See [structure-aware fuzzing documentation](https://github.com/google/fuzzing/blob/master/docs/structure-aware-fuzzing.md) for details.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Custom Mutators}
\p{libFuzzer allows custom mutators for specialized fuzzing:}

\pre{\startverb
extern "C" size_t LLVMFuzzerCustomMutator(uint8_t *Data, size_t Size,
                                          size_t MaxSize, unsigned int Seed) {
    // Custom mutation logic
    return new_size;
}

extern "C" size_t LLVMFuzzerCustomCrossOver(const uint8_t *Data1, size_t Size1,
                                            const uint8_t *Data2, size_t Size2,
                                            uint8_t *Out, size_t MaxOutSize,
                                            unsigned int Seed) {
    // Custom crossover logic
    return new_size;
}
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Performance Tuning}
\pre{\startverb
| Setting | Impact |
|---------|--------|
| `-close_fd_mask=3` | Closes stdout/stderr, speeds up fuzzing |
| `-max_len=<reasonable_size>` | Avoids wasting time on huge inputs |
| `-timeout=<seconds>` | Detects hangs, prevents stuck executions |
| Disable ASan for baseline | 2-4x speed boost (but misses memory bugs) |
| Use `-jobs` and `-workers` | Limited multi-core support |
| Run on Linux | Best platform support and performance |
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Troubleshooting}
\pre{\startverb
| Problem | Cause | Solution |
|---------|-------|----------|
| No crashes found after hours | Poor corpus, low coverage | Add seed inputs, use dictionary, check harness |
| Very slow executions/sec (<100) | Target too complex, excessive logging | Optimize target, use `-close_fd_mask=3`, reduce logging |
| Out of memory | ASan's 20TB virtual memory | Set `-rss_limit_mb=0` to disable RSS limit |
| Fuzzer stops after first crash | Default behavior | Use `-fork=1 -ignore_crashes=1` to continue |
| Can't reproduce crash | Non-determinism in harness/target | Remove random number generation, global state |
| Linking errors with `-fsanitize=fuzzer` | Missing libFuzzer runtime | Ensure using Clang, check LLVM installation |
| GCC project won't compile with Clang | GCC-specific code | Switch to AFL++ with `gcc_plugin` instead |
| Coverage not improving | Corpus plateau | Run longer, add dictionary, improve seeds, check coverage report |
| Crashes but ASan doesn't trigger | Memory error not detected without ASan | Recompile with `-fsanitize=address` |
\stopverb}
}

